# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ios-app-hardening
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The **App Store** is an app marketplace developed and maintained by Apple, for mobile apps and desktop apps on its iOS, macOS and iPadOS operating systems.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The store allows users to browse and download approved apps developed within Apple's iOS SDK.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apps can be downloaded on the iPhone, iPod Touch, or iPad, and some can be transferred to the Apple Watch smartwatch or 4th-generation or newer Apple TVs as extensions of iPhone apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The App Store opened on July 10, 2008, with an initial 500 applications available.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The number of apps peaked at around 2.2 million in 2017, but declined slightly over the next few years as Apple began a process to remove old or 32-bit apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] As of 2024, the store features more than 1.9 million apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In October 2021, the Netherlands Authority for Consumers and Markets (ACM) concluded that in-app commissions from Apple's App Store are anti-competitive and would demand that Apple change its in-app payment system policies.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] While originally developing the iPhone prior to its unveiling in 2007, Apple CEO Steve Jobs did not intend to let third-party developers build native apps for iOS, instead directing them to make web applications for the Safari web browser.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] However, backlash from developers prompted the company to reconsider, with Jobs announcing in October 2007 that Apple would have a software development kit available for developers by February 2008.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Before the official availability of the App Store, users could install third party apps only after a jailbreak of the device.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The iPhone App Store opened on July 10, 2008.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] On July 11, the iPhone 3G was released and came pre-loaded with support for App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] iBeer was one of the earliest successful apps on the App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The app allows users to pretend to drink a beer with their iPhones.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The App Store's early landscape allowed such apps to succeed, with the creators reporting that they made $10,000 to $20,000 a day.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Initially, apps could be free or paid, but then in 2009, Apple added the ability to add in-app purchases which quickly became the dominant way to monetize apps, especially games.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] After the success of Apple's App Store and the launch of similar services by its competitors, the term "app store" has been adopted to refer to any similar service for mobile devices.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] However, Apple applied for a U.S. trademark on the term "App Store" in 2008, which was tentatively approved in early 2011.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] District Judge Phyllis Hamilton, who was presiding over Apple's case against Amazon, said she would "probably" deny Apple's motion to stop Amazon from using the "App Store" name.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In July, Apple was denied preliminary injunction against Amazon's Appstore by a federal judge.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The term *app* has become a popular buzzword; in January 2011, *app* was awarded the honor of being 2010's "Word of the Year" by the American Dialect Society.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] "App" has been used as shorthand for "application" since at least the late 1970s, and in product names since at least 2006, for example, then-named Google Apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple announced Mac App Store, a similar app distribution platform for its macOS personal computer operating system, in October 2010, with the official launch taking place in January 2011 with the release of its 10.6.6 "Snow Leopard" update.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In February 2013, Apple informed developers that they could begin using appstore.com for links to their apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In June at its developer conference, Apple announced an upcoming "Kids" section in App Store, a new section featuring apps categorized by age range, and the section was launched alongside the release of iOS 7 in September 2013.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In 2016, multiple media outlets reported that apps had decreased significantly in popularity.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] *Recode* wrote that "The app boom is over", an editorial in *TechCrunch* stated that "The air of hopelessness that surrounds the mobile app ecosystem is obvious and demoralizing", and *The Verge* wrote that "the original App Store model of selling apps for a buck or two looks antiquated".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Issues included consumer "boredom", a lack of app discoverability, and, as stated by a report from 2014, a lack of new app downloads among smartphone users.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In October 2016, in an effort to improve app discoverability, Apple rolled out the ability for developers to purchase advertising spots in App Store to users in the United States.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The ads, shown at the top of the search results, are based strictly on relevant keywords, and are not used to create profiles on users.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple expanded search ads to the United Kingdom, Australia and New Zealand in April 2017, along with more configurable advertising settings for developers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Search ads were expanded to Canada, Mexico and Switzerland in October 2017.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In December 2017, Apple revamped its search ads program to offer two distinctive versions; "Search Ads Basic" is a pay-per-install program aimed at smaller developers, in which they only pay when users actually install their app.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Search Ads Basic also features an easier setup process and a restricted monthly budget.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] "Search Ads Advanced" is a new name given to the older method, in which developers have to pay whenever users tap on their apps in search results, along with unlimited monthly budgets. .
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The functionality was officially enabled on March 27, 2017 when iOS 10.3 was released to users.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple also offered an iTunes Affiliate Program, which lets people refer others to apps and other iTunes content, along with in-app purchases, for a percentage of sales.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The commission rate for in-app purchases was reduced from 7% to 2.5% in May 2017 and discontinued completely in 2018.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In September 2017, App Store received a major design overhaul with the release of iOS 11.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The new design features a greater focus on editorial content and daily highlights, and introduces a "cleaner and more consistent and colorful look," similar to several of Apple's built-in iOS apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Prior to September 2017, Apple offered a way for users to manage their iOS app purchases through the iTunes computer software.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In September, version 12.7 of iTunes was released, removing the App Store section in the process.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] However, the following month, iTunes 12.6.3 was also released, retaining the App Store, with *9to5Mac* noting that the secondary release was positioned by Apple as "necessary for some businesses performing internal app deployments".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In December 2017, Apple announced that developers could offer applications for pre-order, letting them make apps visible in the store between 2–90 days ahead of release.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] On January 4, 2018, Apple announced that the App Store had a record-breaking holiday season according to a new press release.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] During the week starting on Christmas Eve, a record number of customers made App Store purchases, spending more than $890 million in that seven-day period.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] On New Year's Day 2018 alone, customers made $300 million in purchases.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In September 2019, Apple launched Apple Arcade, a subscription service for video games within the App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In March 2020, Apple made "Sign in with Apple" mandatory for any apps that use third party logins (such as signing in with a Google account).
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] As part of the new App Store guidelines, the deadline for developers to implement the feature was April 30.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In 2019 and 2020, Apple was frequently criticized by other companies such as Spotify, Airbnb and Hey and regulators for potentially running the App Store as a monopoly and overcharging developers, and was the target of lawsuits and investigations in the EU and United States.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] A conflict between Epic Games, the creator of the Fortnite game, and Apple, led to the lawsuit Epic Games v.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In December 2020, Apple announced that they would introduce a "Small Business Program" which lowers Apple's revenue cut for app developers making less than USD 1 million per year from 30% to 15%.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Additionally, governments such as in China, India and Russia have increasingly required Apple to remove specific apps, with the threatened removal of some apps often becoming part of geopolitical feuds.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In January 2022, Apple added support for unlisted apps to the App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] These apps can only be downloaded via direct links, and do not appear as search results.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Later in December 2022, a report by Bloomberg noted that the company had begun making preparations for opening up sideloading and alternative app stores on iOS, as compliance with the EU's Digital Markets Act that had passed in September of that year.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The same report also noted Apple planned to open up the NFC and camera systems on iOS, and the Find My network to AirTag competitors like Tile.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Following a European Commission antitrust investigation, on January 25, 2024, Apple allowed game streaming apps and services, such as Xbox Cloud Streaming and GeForce Now, on the App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple also allowed iPhone users in the European Union to use third-party app stores and browser engines.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple lawsuit, a 2021 court ruling forced Apple to allow developers to include external payment links in apps, which Apple initially complied with by adding a 27% commission and restrictive warnings.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In April 2025, the court ruled Apple violated the injunction, ordering the removal of all commissions and restrictions on external payment links.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple appealed the decision but complied by May 2025, allowing apps like Fortnite to return with unrestricted payment options.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The appeal remains ongoing as of August 2025.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In November 2025, Apple launched a web interface at apps.apple.com, allowing users to browse and search for apps written for iPhone, iPad, Mac, Apple Vision Pro, Apple Watch, Apple TV in a web browser, in addition to the existing native apps on those devices.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The iOS SDK (Software development kit) allows for the development of mobile apps on iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] It is a free download for users of Mac personal computers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] It is not available for Microsoft Windows PCs.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The SDK contains sets giving developers access to various functions and services of iOS devices, such as hardware and software attributes.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] It also contains an iPhone simulator to mimic the look and feel of the device on the computer while developing.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] New versions of the SDK accompany new versions of iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In order to test applications, get technical support, and distribute apps through App Store, developers are required to subscribe to the Apple Developer Program.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Combined with Xcode, the iOS SDK helps developers write iOS apps using officially supported programming languages, including Swift and Objective-C.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Other companies have also created tools that allow for the development of native iOS apps using their respective programming languages.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] To publish apps on App Store, developers must pay a $99 yearly fee for access to Apple's Developer Program.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple announced that, in the United States starting in 2018, it would waive the fee for nonprofit organizations and governments.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Fee waivers have, since 2020, been extended to non-profits, educational organizations and governments in additional countries.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Developers have a few options for monetizing their applications.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The "Free Model" enables free apps, increasing likelihood of engagement.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The "Freemium Model" makes the app download free, but users are offered optional additional features in-app that require payments.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The "Subscription Model" enables ongoing monetization through renewable transactions.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The "Paid Model" makes the app itself a paid download and offers no additional features.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Less frequently, the "Paymium Model" has both a paid app downloads and paid in-app content.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In-app subscriptions were originally introduced for magazines, newspapers and music apps in February 2011, giving developers 70% of revenue earned and Apple 30%.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Publishers could also sell digital subscriptions through their website, bypassing Apple's fees, but were not allowed to advertise their website alternative through the apps themselves.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The subscription model saw the firmly established 70/30 revenue split between developers and Apple change into a new 85/15 revenue split if a user stays subscribed to the developer's app for a year, and opens the possibility of subscriptions to all apps, not just select categories.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] App data and insights analyst company App Annie released a report in October 2016, announcing that China had overtaken the United States as Apple's biggest market in App Store revenue.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In the third quarter of 2016, Chinese users spent $1.7 billion vs. approximately $1.5 billion by American users.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In June 2017, Apple announced that App Store had generated over $70 billion in revenue for developers since its 2008 launch.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] By 2020, this had increased to $155 billion, and by 2023 to $ 320 billion.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In 2024 the Apple App Store generated a total of $1.3 trillion in sales.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The App Store is also available on tvOS, the operating system for the Apple TV.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] It was announced on September 9, 2015, at the Apple September 2015 event, alongside the 4th generation Apple TV.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] tvOS ships with development tools for developers. tvOS adds support for an SDK for developers to build apps for the TV including all of the APIs included in iOS 9 such as Metal.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] It also adds an which allows users to browse, download, and install a wide variety of applications.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In addition, developers can now use their own interface inside of their application rather than only being able to use Apple's interface.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Since tvOS is based on iOS, it is easy to port existing iOS apps to the Apple TV with Xcode while making only a few refinements to the app to better suit the larger screen.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple provides Xcode free of charge to all registered Apple developers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] To develop for the new Apple TV, it is necessary to make a parallax image for the application icon.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In order to do this, Apple provides a Parallax exporter and previewer in the development tools for the Apple TV.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] On July 10, 2008, Apple's then-CEO Steve Jobs told *USA Today* that App Store contained 500 third-party applications for the iPhone and the iPod Touch, and of these 125 were free.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Ten million downloads were recorded in the first weekend.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] By September, the number of available apps had increased to 3,000, with over 100 million downloads.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Over the years, the store has surpassed multiple major milestones, including 50,000, 100,000, 250,000, 500,000, 1 million, and 2 million apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The billionth application was downloaded on April 24, 2009.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The number of apps on the app store shrank for the first time in 2017 as Apple began to remove older apps which did not comply with current app guidelines and technologies.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] As of 2020, it was estimated to house around 1.8 million apps, and as of 2024 Apple reported a total of more than 1.9 million apps available on the App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The iPad was released in April 2010, with approximately 3,000 apps available.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] By July 2011, 16 months after the release, there were over 100,000 apps available designed specifically for the device.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple publishes a list on a yearly basis, giving credit to the apps with the highest number of downloads in the past year.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] These are the most downloaded iOS applications and the highest revenue-generating iOS applications of all time.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple rates applications worldwide based on their content, and determines the age group for which each is appropriate.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] According to the iPhone OS 3.0 launch event, the iPhone allows blocking of objectionable apps in the iPhone's settings.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The rating system received an overhaul for iOS 26 in 2025.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Applications are subject to approval by Apple, as outlined in the SDK agreement, for basic reliability testing and other analysis.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Applications may still be distributed "ad hoc" if they are rejected, by the author manually submitting a request to Apple to license the application to individual iPhones, although Apple may withdraw the ability for authors to do this at a later date.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] As of 2013, Apple employed mostly static analysis for their app review process, which means that dynamic code reassembly techniques could defeat the review process.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In June 2017, Apple updated its App Store review guidelines to specify that app developers will no longer have the ability to use custom prompts for encouraging users to leave reviews for their apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] With the release of iOS 11 in late 2017, Apple also let developers choose whether to keep current app reviews when updating their apps or to reset.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Additionally, another update to App Store policies allows users to optionally "tip" content creators, by voluntarily sending them money.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Some of the information shared with third parties was found to be in violation of the apps' own privacy regulations.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple responded to the controversy by introducing "privacy nutrition labels" on the App Store, forcing all apps to disclose their data use.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In November 2012, Boyfriend Maker, which is a dating sim game, was removed due to "reports of references to violent sexual acts and paedophilia" deemed inappropriate to Boyfriend Maker's age rating of 4+.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] A revised version called Boyfriend Plus was approved by Apple in April 2013.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In March 2013, HiddenApps was approved and appeared in App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The app provided access to developer diagnostic menus, allowed for stock apps to be hidden, and enabled an opt-out feature for iAds, Apple's developer-driven advertisement system.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The app was removed shortly afterwards for violating guidelines.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In April 2013, Apple removed AppGratis, a then-successful app store market that promoted paid apps by offering one for free each day.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple did, however, tell the developers they were "welcome to resubmit" after changing the app, though there was "not much hope that it could survive in anything like its current incarnation".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In September 2015, it was discovered that "hundreds" of apps submitted and approved on App Store were using XcodeGhost, a malicious version of the Xcode development software.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The issues prompted Apple to remove infected apps from the store and issue a statement that it was "working with the developers to make sure they're using the proper version of Xcode".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] A security firm later published lists of infected apps, including a China-only version of *Angry Birds 2*, CamCard, Lifesmart, TinyDeal.com, and WeChat.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In June 2017, a scamming trend was discovered on the store, in which developers make apps built on non-existent services, attach in-app purchase subscriptions to the opening dialogue, then buy App Store search advertising space to get the app into the higher rankings.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In one instance, an app by the name of "Mobile protection :Clean & Security VPN" [*sic*] would require payments of $99.99 for a seven-day subscription after a short trial.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple has not yet responded to the issues.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In addition, Apple has removed software licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL) from App Store, due to text in Apple's Terms of Service agreement imposing digital rights management and proprietary legal terms incompatible with the terms of the GPL.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] As of December 2025, the App Store hosts Absher (application), a stalkerware app by the Saudi government.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] On September 1, 2016, Apple announced that starting September 7, it would be removing old apps that do not function as intended or that do not follow current review guidelines.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Developers will be warned and given 30 days to update their apps, but apps that crash on startup will be removed immediately.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Additionally, the app names registered by developers cannot exceed 50 characters, in an attempt to stop developers from inserting long descriptions or irrelevant terms in app names to improve the app's ranking in App Store search results.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] App intelligence firm Sensor Tower revealed in November 2016 that Apple, as promised from its September announcement of removing old apps, had removed 47,300 apps from App Store in October 2016, a 238 percent increase of its prior number of average monthly app removals.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In June 2017, *TechCrunch* reported that Apple had turned its app removal focus on apps copying functionality from other, popular apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] An example cited included "if a popular game like *Flappy Bird* or *Red Ball* hits the charts, there will be hundreds or thousands of clones within weeks that attempt to capitalize on the initial wave of popularity".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The report also noted removals of music apps serving pirated tracks.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The publication wrote that, since the initial September app removals began, Apple had removed "multiple hundreds of thousands" of apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In December 2017, a new report from *TechCrunch* stated that Apple had begun enforcing new restrictions on the use of "commercialized template or app generation services".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Originally introduced as part of Apple's 2017 developer conference, new App Store guidelines allow the company to ban apps making use of templates or commercial app services.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] This affected many small businesses, with *TechCrunch*'s report citing that "local retailers, restaurants, small fitness studios, nonprofits, churches and other organizations" benefit from using templates or app services due to minimal costs.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Developers had received notice from Apple with a January 1, 2018 deadline to change their respective apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple had told us you aren't being targeted by this from a quality standpoint.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] So being hit now under the umbrella of spam is shocking to every quality developer out there and all the good actors".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Furthermore, the latter company stated that "there's only so much you can do with apps that perform the same utility – ordering food".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] A third company said that "Rule 4.2.6 is a concrete illustration of the danger of Apple's dominant position", and a fourth said that "They've wiped out pretty much an entire industry.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Not just DIY tools like AppMakr, but also development suites like Titanium".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple prevented over $2.2 billion in potentially fraudulent transactions on its App Store in 2025 and rejected over 2 million app submissions for violating App Store review guidelines.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In January 2017, Apple complied with a request from the Chinese government to remove the Chinese version of *The New York Times*' app.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] This followed the government's efforts in 2012 to block the *Times*' website after stories of hidden wealth among family members of then-leader of China, Wen Jiabao, were published.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In a statement, an Apple spokesperson told the media that "we have been informed that the app is in violation of local regulations", though would not specify which regulations, and added that "As a result the app must be taken down off the China app store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] When this situation changes the app store will once again offer the *New York Times* app for download in China".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The following July, it was reported that Apple had begun to remove listings in China for apps that circumvent government Internet censorship policies and new laws restricting virtual private network (VPN) services.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple issued a statement, explaining that the app removals were a result of developers not complying with new laws in China requiring a government license for businesses offering VPNs, and that "These apps remain available in all other markets where they do business".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In an earnings call the following month, Cook elaborated on the recent news, explainining that "We would obviously rather not remove the apps, but like we do in other countries, we follow the law wherever we do business".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Besides VPN services, a number of Internet calling apps, including Microsoft's Skype, were also removed from the Chinese App Store in 2017, with Apple telling *The New York Times* that, similar to the VPN apps, these new apps also violated local law.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Microsoft explained to *BBC News* that its Skype app had been "temporarily removed" and that it was "working to reinstate the app as soon as possible", though many news outlets reported on the Chinese government's increased efforts and pressure to crack down on Internet freedom.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Following Apple CEO Tim Cook's appearance at China's World Internet Conference in December 2017, free speech and human rights activists criticized Cook and the company.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The version of cyberspace the Chinese government is building is a decidedly dystopian one, and I don't think anyone would want to share in this 'common future.' Apple should have spoken out against it, not endorsed it." U.S.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Senator Patrick Leahy told *CNBC* that "American tech companies have become leading champions of free expression.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] But that commitment should not end at our borders. ...
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Cook told *Reuters* that "My hope over time is that some of the things, the couple of things that's been pulled, come back.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] I have great hope on that and great optimism on that".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] However, *TechCrunch*'s Jon Russell criticized this line of thinking, writing that "Firstly, Apple didn't just remove a 'couple of things' from the reach of China-based users", but rather "a couple of hundred" apps, acknowledging that "even that is under counting".
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In August 2018, as a result of Chinese regulations, 25,000 illegal apps were pulled down by Apple from the App Store in China.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In October 2019, Apple rejected, approved, and finally removed an app used by participants in the 2019–20 Hong Kong protests.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple began removing thousands of video game apps from their platform in China during December 2020 in accordance to regulations regarding licensing enacted by the country's Cyberspace Administration, in many cases without explicitly stating the offences grounding their removal.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple released a memo that month telling developers of premium games and apps with in-app purchases had until December 31 to submit proof of a government license.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In August 2023, at the request of the Chinese government, Apple took down more than 100 AI-related apps similar to ChatGPT in the Chinese app store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] According to the regulations of Chinese government, new apps on the China app store from September 2023 must be licensed by the Chinese government.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Older apps must obtain a license before March 2024.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In April 2026, Apple took down BitChat at the request of the Chinese government.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple removed the *Smart Voting* app from the App Store before the 2021 Russian legislative election.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The application, which had been created by associates of imprisoned opposition leader Alexei Navalny, offered voting advice for all voting districts in Russia.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] It was removed after a meeting with Russian Federation Council officials on September 16, 2021.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple also reportedly disabled its iCloud Private Relay privacy feature which masks users' browsing activity.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Russian opposition figures condemned these moves as political censorship.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In 2024, Russian regulator Roskomnadzor asked Apple to take down 25 VPN apps from the Russian App Store, but Apple quietly took down more.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In October 2025, following a request by the Trump administration, Apple removed ICE tracking apps, which could notify users about the presence of Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents in their area.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In November 2019, Apple removed all applications related to vaping from the App Store, citing warning from health experts.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple made this decision to reduce the promotion of e-cigarette use.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Apple has faced criticism, lawsuits and government investigations alleging that its control over the distribution of iOS and iPadOS apps through the App Store constituted monopolistic practices.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] On August 13, 2020, Epic Games updated *Fortnite* across all platforms, including the iOS version, to reduce the price of "V-Bucks" (the in-game currency) by 20% if they purchased directly from Epic.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] For iOS users, if they purchased through the Apple storefront, they were not given this discount, as Epic said they could not extend the discount due to the 30% revenue cut taken by Apple.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Within hours, Apple had removed *Fortnite* from their storefronts, stating the means of bypassing their payment systems violated the terms of service.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Epic immediately filed separate lawsuits against Apple and Google for antitrust and anticompetitive behavior in the United States District Court for the Northern District of California.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] The primary opposing argument is: 'Smartphone makers can do whatever they want.' This as an awful notion.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] In a September 2021 ruling in the first part of the case, Judge Yvonne Gonzalez Rogers decided in favor of Apple on nine of ten counts, but found against Apple on its anti-steering policies under the California Unfair Competition Law.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] Rogers prohibited Apple from stopping developers from informing users of other payment systems within apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/app-store-apple] While Apple implemented App Store policies to allow developers to link to alternative payment options, the policies still required the developer to provide a 27% revenue share back to Apple, and heavily restricted how they could be shown in apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] As of December 2023, Apple's App Store contains more than 3.8 million iOS mobile apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Like macOS, it includes components of the Mach microkernel and FreeBSD.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Although some parts of iOS are open source under the Apple Public Source License and other licenses, iOS is proprietary software.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In 2005, when Steve Jobs began planning the iPhone, he stated that he had a choice to either "shrink the Mac, which would be an epic feat of engineering, or enlarge the iPod".
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Jobs favored the former approach but pitted the Macintosh and iPod teams, led by Scott Forstall and Tony Fadell, respectively, against each other in an internal competition, with Forstall winning by creating iPhone OS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The decision enabled the success of the iPhone as a platform for third-party developers: using a well-known desktop operating system as its basis allowed the many third-party Mac developers to write software for the iPhone with minimal retraining.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Forstall was also responsible for creating a software development kit for programmers to build iPhone apps, as well as an App Store within iTunes.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The operating system was unveiled with the iPhone at the Macworld Conference & Expo on January 9, 2007, and released in June of that year.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] At the time of its unveiling in January, Steve Jobs claimed: "iPhone runs OS X" and runs "desktop class applications", but at the time of the iPhone's release, the operating system was renamed "iPhone OS".
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Initially, third-party native applications were not supported.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Jobs' reasoning was that developers could build web applications through the Safari web browser that "would behave like native apps on the iPhone".
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In October 2007, Apple announced that a native software development kit (SDK) was under development and that they planned to put it "in developers' hands in February".
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On March 6, 2008, Apple held a press event, announcing the iPhone SDK.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The iOS App Store was opened on July 10, 2008, with an initial 500 applications available.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] As of March 2016, 1 million apps are natively compatible with the iPad tablet computer.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] These apps have collectively been downloaded more than 130 billion times.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] App intelligence firm Sensor Tower estimated that the App Store would reach 5 million apps by 2020.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In September 2007, Apple announced the iPod Touch, a redesigned iPod based on the iPhone form factor.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It also includes a mobile version of Safari for web browsing, as well as access to the App Store, iTunes Library, iBookstore, Contacts, and Notes.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Content is downloadable via Wi-Fi and optional 3G service or synced through the user's computer.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] AT&T was initially the sole U.S. provider of 3G wireless access for the iPad.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In June 2010, Apple rebranded iPhone OS as "iOS".
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The trademark "IOS" had been used by Cisco for over a decade for its operating system, IOS, used on its routers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] To avoid any potential lawsuit, Apple licensed the "IOS" trademark from Cisco.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The Apple Watch smartwatch was announced by Tim Cook on September 9, 2014, being introduced as a product with health and fitness-tracking.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It uses watchOS as its operating system; watchOS is based on iOS, with new features created specially for the Apple Watch such as an activity tracking app.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In October 2016, Apple opened its first iOS Developer Academy in Naples inside University of Naples Federico II's new campus.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The course is completely free, aimed at acquiring specific technical skills on the creation and management of applications for the Apple ecosystem platforms.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] At the academy there are also issues of business administration (business planning and business management with a focus on digital opportunities) and there is a path dedicated to the design of graphical interfaces.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Students have the opportunity to participate in the "Enterprise Track", an in-depth training experience on the entire life cycle of an app, from design to implementation, to security, troubleshooting, data storage and cloud usage.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] As of 2020, the academy graduated almost a thousand students from all over the world, who have worked on 400 app ideas and have already published about 50 apps on the iOS App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In the 2018–2019 academic year, students from more than 30 countries arrived.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] 35 of these have been selected to attend the Worldwide Developer Conference, the annual Apple Developer Conference held annually in California in early June.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On June 3, 2019, iPadOS, the branded version of iOS for iPad, was announced during the WWDC 2019 keynote; it was launched on September 25, 2019.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On June 9, 2025, at WWDC 2025, Apple introduced iOS 26.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The version number indicates the year following the year in which the version was introduced; this numbering scheme is now being used for all Apple operating systems, keeping their version numbers synchronized.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On June 8, 2026, at WWDC 2026, Apple introduced iOS 27.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It introduces Siri AI, a new model designed by Apple in collaboration with Google.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Siri AI is able to handle significantly more complex tasks, such as making shortcuts in the Shortcuts app and planning advanced routes.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The revamped Siri is similar to an AI chatbot, and it will receive an app where users can look at their past conversations.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The iOS user interface is based upon direct manipulation, using multi-touch gestures such as *swipe*, *tap*, *pinch*, and *reverse pinch*.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Interface control elements include sliders, switches, and buttons.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Internal accelerometers are used by some applications to respond to shaking the device (one common result is the undo command) or rotating it in three dimensions (one common result is switching between portrait and landscape mode).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Various accessibility described in § Accessibility functions enable users with vision and hearing disabilities to properly use iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The lock screen shows the time and a user's lock screen widgets, which display timely information from apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The lock screen also has two buttons, called Controls, which are only available on iPhone.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] These default to flashlight and camera, but they can be customized to any control available in Control Center and can also be removed.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Along the top of the screen is a status bar, showing information about the device and its connectivity.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It is possible to manage brightness, volume, wireless connections, music player, etc.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Scrolling from the top left to the bottom (or top to bottom on iPhones with Touch ID) will open the Notification Center, which in the latest versions of iOS is very similar to the lock screen.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It displays notifications in chronological order and groups them by application.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] From the notifications of some apps it is possible to interact directly, for example by replying to a message directly from it.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Both can be found in the Notification Center, and show for a set amount of time on the lock screen (unless the user has Notification Center allowed when locked).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On iPhones with Touch ID, screenshots can be created with the simultaneous press of the home and power buttons.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In comparison to Android, which requires the buttons to be held down, a short press does suffice on iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On iPhone with Face ID, screenshots are captured using the volume-up and power buttons instead.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The camera application used a skeuomorphic closing camera shutter animation prior to iOS 7.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Since then, it uses a simple short blackout effect.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Some camera settings such as video resolution and frame rate are not adjustable through the camera interface itself, but are outsourced to the system settings.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A new feature in iOS 13 called "context menus" shows related actions when you touch and hold an item.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] When the context menu is displayed, the background is blurred.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] To choose from a few options, a selection control is used.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Selectors can appear anchored at the bottom or in line with the content (called date selectors).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Date selectors take on the appearance of any other selection control, but with a column for day, month, and optionally year.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Alerts appear in the center of the screen, but there are also alerts that scroll up from the bottom of the screen (called "action panels").
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Destructive actions (such as eliminating any element) are colored red.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The official font of iOS is San Francisco.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It is designed for small text readability, and is used throughout the operating system, including third-party apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The icons are 180x180px in size for iPhones with a larger screen, usually models over 6 inches, including iPhone 11 Pro and iPhone 8 Plus, while they are 120x120px on iPhones with smaller displays.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The home screen appears whenever the user unlocks the device, presses the physical "Home" button while in an app, or swipes up from the bottom of the screen using the home bar.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The screen has a status bar across the top to display data, such as time, battery level, and signal strength.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The rest of the screen is devoted to the current application.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] When a passcode is set and a user switches on the device, the passcode must be entered at the Lock Screen before access to the Home screen is granted.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iPhone OS 3, Spotlight was introduced, allowing users to search media, apps, emails, contacts, messages, reminders, calendar events, and similar content.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 7 and later, Spotlight is accessed by pulling down anywhere on the home screen (except for the top and bottom edges that open Notification Center and Control Center).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 9, there are two ways to access Spotlight.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] As with iOS 7 and 8, pulling down on any homescreen will show Spotlight.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] However, it can also be accessed as it was in iOS versions 3 through 6.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This endows Spotlight with Siri suggestions, which include app suggestions, contact suggestions and news.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 10, Spotlight is at the top of the now-dedicated "Today" panel.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] With the release of iPhone OS 3.2, users gained the ability to set a wallpaper for the Home Screen.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS 7 introduced a parallax effect on the Home Screen, which shifts the device's wallpaper and icons in response to the movement of the device, creating a 3D effect and an illusion of floating icons.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This effect is also visible in the tab view of Mail and Safari.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Researchers found that users organize icons on their homescreens based on usage frequency and relatedness of the applications, as well as for reasons of usability and aesthetics.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS originally used Helvetica as the system font.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Apple switched to Helvetica Neue exclusively for the iPhone 4 and its Retina Display, and retained Helvetica as the system font for older iPhone devices on iOS 4.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] With iOS 7, Apple announced that they would change the system font to Helvetica Neue Light, a decision that sparked criticism for inappropriate usage of a light, thin typeface for low-resolution mobile screens.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Apple eventually chose Helvetica Neue instead.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The release of iOS 7 also introduced the ability to scale text or apply other forms of text accessibility changes through Settings.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] With iOS 9, Apple changed the font to San Francisco, an Apple-designed font aimed at maximum legibility and font consistency across its product lineup.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS 4 introduced folders, which can be created by dragging an application on top of another, and from then on, more items can be added to the folder using the same procedure.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A title for the folder is automatically selected by the category of applications inside, but the name can also be edited by the user.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] When apps inside folders receive notification badges, the individual numbers of notifications are added up and the total number is displayed as a notification badge on the folder itself.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Originally, folders on an iPhone could include up to 12 apps, while folders on iPad could include 20.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] With increasing display sizes on newer iPhone hardware, iOS 7 updated the folders with pages similar to the home screen layout, allowing for a significant expansion of folder functionality.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Each page of a folder can contain up to nine apps, and there can be 15 pages in total, allowing for a total of 135 apps in a single folder.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 9, Apple updated folder sizes for iPad hardware, allowing for 16 apps per page, still at 15 pages maximum, increasing the total to 240 apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Before iOS 5, notifications were delivered in a modal window and could not be viewed after being dismissed.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 5, Apple introduced Notification Center, which allows users to view a history of notifications.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The user can tap a notification to open its corresponding app, or clear it.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Notifications are now delivered in banners that appear briefly at the top of the screen.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] If a user taps a received notification, the application that sent the notification will be opened.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Users can also choose to view notifications in modal alert windows by adjusting the application's notification settings.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Introduced with iOS 8, widgets are now accessible through the Notification Center, defined by 3rd parties.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] When an app sends a notification while closed, a red badge appears on its icon.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This badge tells the user, at a glance, how many notifications that app has sent.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS devices come with preinstalled apps developed by Apple including Mail, Maps, TV, Music, FaceTime, Wallet, Health, and many more.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Applications ("apps") are the most general form of application software that can be installed on iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] They are downloaded from the official catalog of the App Store digital store, where apps are subjected to security checks before being made available to users.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In June 2017, Apple updated its guidelines to specify that app developers will no longer have the ability to use custom prompts for encouraging users to leave reviews for their apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] IOS applications can also be installed directly from an IPA file provided by the software distributor, via unofficial ways.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] They are written using iOS Software Development Kit (SDK) and, often, combined with Xcode, using officially supported programming languages, including Swift and Objective-C.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Applications for iOS are mostly built using components of UIKit, a programming framework.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It allows applications to have a consistent look and feel with the OS, nevertheless offering customization.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Elements automatically update along with iOS updates, automatically including new interface rules.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] UIKit elements are very adaptable, this allows developers to design a single app that looks the same on any iOS device.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In addition to defining the iOS interface, UIKit defines the functionality of the application.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] At first, Apple did not intend to release an SDK to developers, because they did not want third-party apps to be developed for iOS, building web apps instead.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] However, this technology never entered into common use, this led Apple to change its opinion, so in October 2007 the SDK for developers was announced, finally released on March 6, 2008.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The SDK includes an inclusive set of development tools, including an audio mixer and an iPhone simulator.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] To test the application, get technical support, and distribute applications through App Store, developers are required to subscribe to the Apple Developer Program.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Over the years, the Apple Store apps surpassed multiple major milestones, including 50,000, 100,000, 250,000, 500,000, 1 million, and 2 million apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The billionth application was installed on April 24, 2009.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] App Library automatically categorizes apps into folders based on their function or type and includes an alphabetical list of all installed apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] For example, it might group all social media apps into one folder and productivity apps into another.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Users can quickly find and access apps by using the search bar at the top of the App Library.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Users can choose to hide specific app pages from the home screen, making it easier to focus on the apps they use most frequently.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS enforces strict sandboxing to maintain security and privacy.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Apps are generally limited to accessing their own containers and specific system-provided directories, such as the Photos library.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] To access files outside of their sandbox, iOS uses mechanisms like document pickers, file providers, and app extensions.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS 8 introduced the Document Picker and Document Provider extensions as part of the document interaction controller.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This allows apps to open, save, and interact with documents stored in a central location or cloud storage services.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] With iOS 11, Apple introduced the Files app and the File Provider extension, providing a central location for users to manage and organize their files.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Apps can integrate with the Files app to make their documents accessible and editable directly from the Files app.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] These files can be accessed across multiple devices as long as the user is signed in with the same Apple ID.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS offers various accessibility features to help users with vision and hearing disabilities.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] One major feature, VoiceOver, provides a voice reading information on the screen, including contextual buttons, icons, links and other user interface elements, and allows the user to navigate the operating system through gestures.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Any apps with default controls and developed with a UIKit framework gets VoiceOver functionality built in.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] One example includes holding up the iPhone to take a photo, with VoiceOver describing the photo scenery.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] As part of a "Made for iPhone" program, introduced with the release of iOS 7 in 2013, Apple has developed technology to use Bluetooth and a special technology protocol to let compatible third-party equipment connect with iPhones and iPads for streaming audio directly to a user's ears.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Additional customization available for Made for iPhone products include battery tracking and adjustable sound settings for different environments.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Building into the core of our products supports a vision of an inclusive world where opportunity and access to information are barrier-free, empowering individuals with disabilities to achieve their goals".
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Criticism has been aimed at iOS depending on both internet connection (either WiFi or through iTunes) and a working SIM card upon first activation.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This restriction has been loosened in iOS 12, which no longer requires the latter.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Multitasking for iOS was first released in June 2010 along with the release of iOS 4.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Only certain devices—iPhone 4, iPhone 3GS, and iPod Touch 3rd generation—were able to multitask.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The iPad did not get multitasking until iOS 4.2.1 in that November.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The implementation of multitasking in iOS has been criticized for its approach, which limits the work that applications in the background can perform to a limited function set and requires application developers to add explicit support for it.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Before iOS 4, multitasking was limited to a selection of the applications Apple included on the device.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Users could however "jailbreak" their device in order to unofficially multitask.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 7, Apple introduced a new multitasking feature, providing all apps with the ability to perform background updates.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This feature prefers to update the user's most frequently used apps and prefers to use Wi-Fi networks over a cellular network, without markedly reducing the device's battery life.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 4.0 to iOS 6.x, double-clicking the home button activates the application switcher.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A scrollable dock-style interface appears from the bottom, moving the contents of the screen up.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Choosing an icon switches to an application.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] To the far left are icons which function as music controls, a rotation lock, and on iOS 4.2 and above, a volume controller.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] With the introduction of iOS 7, double-clicking the home button also activates the application switcher.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] However, unlike previous versions it displays screenshots of open applications on top of the icon and horizontal scrolling allows for browsing through previous apps, and it is possible to close applications by dragging them up, similar to how WebOS handled multiple cards.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Now, instead of the home screen appearing at the leftmost of the application switcher, it appears rightmost.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 11, the application switcher receives a major redesign.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In the iPad, the Control Center and app switcher are combined.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The app switcher in the iPad can also be accessed by swiping up from the bottom.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In the iPhone, the app switcher cannot be accessed if there are no apps in the RAM.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 4.0 to iOS 6.x, briefly holding the icons in the application switcher makes them "jiggle" (similarly to the homescreen) and allows the user to *force* quit the applications by tapping the red minus circle that appears at the corner of the app's icon.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Clearing applications from multitasking stayed the same from iOS 4.0 through 6.1.6, the last version of iOS 6.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] As of iOS 7, the process has become faster and easier.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In iOS 7, instead of holding the icons to close them, they are closed by simply swiping them upwards off the screen.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Up to three apps can be cleared at a time compared to one in versions up to iOS 6.1.6.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Task completion allows apps to continue a certain task after the app has been suspended.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] As of iOS 4.0, apps can request up to ten minutes to complete a task in the background.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This doesn't extend to background uploads and downloads though (e.g. if a user starts a download in one application, it won't finish if they switch away from the application).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Siri (/ˈsɪri/) is a virtual assistant integrated into iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The assistant uses voice queries and a natural-language user interface to answer questions, make recommendations, and perform actions by delegating requests to a set of Internet services.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The software adapts to users' individual language usages, searches, and preferences, with continuing use.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Originally released as an app for iOS in February 2010, it was acquired by Apple two months later, and then integrated into iPhone 4S at its release in October 2011.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] At that time, the separate app was also removed from the iOS App Store.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Siri supports a wide range of user commands, including performing phone actions, checking basic information, scheduling events and reminders, handling device settings, searching the Internet, navigating areas, finding information on entertainment, and is able to engage with iOS-integrated apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] With the release of iOS 10 in 2016, Apple opened up limited third-party access to Siri, including third-party messaging apps, as well as payments, ride-sharing, and Internet calling apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Game Center is an online multiplayer "social gaming network" released by Apple.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It allows users to "invite friends to play a game, start a multiplayer game through matchmaking, track their achievements, and compare their high scores on a leaderboard." iOS 5 and above adds support for profile photos.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Game Center was announced during an iOS 4 preview event hosted by Apple on April 8, 2010.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A preview was released to registered Apple developers in August.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It was released on September 8, 2010, with iOS 4.1 on iPhone 4, iPhone 3GS, and iPod Touch 2nd generation through 4th generation.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Game Center made its public debut on the iPad with iOS 4.2.1.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] There is no support for the iPhone 3G, original iPhone and the first-generation iPod Touch (the latter two devices did not have Game Center because they did not get iOS 4).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] However, Game Center is unofficially available on the iPhone 3G via a hack.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The instruction set architectures supported by iOS are the ARM architectures.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS powers almost exclusively Apple hardware.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It is used for all iPhones and iPod Touch devices.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Further, Apple Watches, Apple TVs, and iPads either also use iOS for some models or use OSes based on iOS for other models.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The iOS software development kit (SDK) allows for the development of mobile apps that can run on iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] While originally developing iPhone prior to its unveiling in 2007, Apple's then-CEO Steve Jobs did not intend to let third-party developers build native apps for iOS, instead directing them to make web applications for the Safari web browser.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The SDK is a free download for users of Mac personal computers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Apple provides major updates to the iOS operating system annually.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Since iOS 5, the primary method of delivery has been over-the-air.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Updates are also available using iTunes on older versions of macOS and Windows, using Finder on macOS starting with macOS Catalina, and using the Apple Devices app on Windows starting with Windows 10 version 22H2.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The device checks an XML-based PLIST file on mesu.apple.com for updates.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Updates are delivered as unencrypted ZIP files.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Updates are checked for regularly, and are downloaded and installed automatically if enabled.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Otherwise, the user can install them manually or are prompted to allow automatic installation overnight if plugged in and connected to Wi-Fi.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iPod Touch users originally had to pay for system software updates due to accounting rules that designated it not a "subscription device" like the iPhone or Apple TV, causing many iPod Touch owners not to update.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In September 2009, a change in accounting rules won tentative approval, affecting Apple's earnings and stock price, and allowing iPod Touch updates to be delivered free of charge.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Apple significantly extended the cycle of updates for iOS-supported devices over the years.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The iPhone (1st generation) and iPhone 3G only received two major iOS updates, while later models had support for three to seven major updates.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS uses the XNU kernel included in the Darwin operating system and used by macOS, adapted to work with devices that run iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Since its initial release, iOS has been subject to a variety of different hacks centered around adding functionality not allowed by Apple.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Prior to the 2008 debut of Apple's native iOS App Store, the primary motive for jailbreaking was to bypass Apple's purchase mechanism for installing the App Store's native applications.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Apple claimed that it would not release iOS software updates designed specifically to break these tools (other than applications that perform SIM unlocking); however, with each subsequent iOS update, previously un-patched jailbreak exploits are usually patched.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] When a device is booting, it loads Apple's own kernel initially, so a jailbroken device must be exploited and have the kernel patched each time it is booted up.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] An *untethered* jailbreak uses exploits that are powerful enough to allow the user to turn their device off and back on at will, with the device starting up completely, and the kernel will be patched without the help of a computer – in other words, it will be jailbroken even after each reboot.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A tethered jailbreak is only able to temporarily jailbreak the device during a single boot.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] If the user turns the device off and then boots it back up without the help of a jailbreak tool, the device will no longer be running a patched kernel, and it may get stuck in a partially started state, such as Recovery Mode.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In order for the device to start completely and with a patched kernel, it must be "re-jailbroken" with a computer (using the "boot tethered" feature of a tool) each time it is turned on.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] All changes to the files on the device (such as installed package files or edited system files) will persist between reboots, including changes that can only function if the device is jailbroken (such as installed package files).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In more recent years, two other solutions have been created – *semi-tethered* and *semi-untethered*.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A semi-tethered solution is one where the device is able to start up on its own, but it will no longer have a patched kernel, and therefore will not be able to run modified code.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] It will, however, still be usable for normal functions, just like stock iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] To start with a patched kernel, the user must start the device with the help of the jailbreak tool.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A semi-untethered jailbreak gives the ability to start the device on its own.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On first boot, the device will not be running a patched kernel.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] However, rather than having to run a tool from a computer to apply the kernel patches, the user is able to re-jailbreak their device with the help of an app (usually sideloaded using Cydia Impactor) running on their device.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In the case of the iOS 9.2-9.3.3 and 64-bit 10.x jailbreaks, Safari-based exploits were available, thereby meaning websites could be used to re-jailbreak.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In more detail: Each iOS device has a bootchain that tries to make sure only trusted/signed code is loaded.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] A device with a tethered jailbreak is able to boot up with the help of a jailbreaking tool because the tool executes exploits via USB that bypass parts of that "chain of trust", bootstrapping to a pwned (no signature check) iBEC, or iBoot to finish the boot process.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Since the arrival of Apple's native iOS App Store, and—along with it—third-party applications, the general motives for jailbreaking have changed.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] People jailbreak for many different reasons, including gaining filesystem access, installing custom device themes, and modifying SpringBoard.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] An additional motivation is that it may enable the installation of pirated apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] On some devices, jailbreaking also makes it possible to install alternative operating systems, such as Android and the Linux kernel.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Primarily, users jailbreak their devices because of the limitations of iOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Depending on the method used, the effects of jailbreaking may be permanent or temporary.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In 2010, the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF) successfully convinced the U.S.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Copyright Office to allow an exemption to the general prohibition on circumvention of copyright protection systems under the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA).
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The exemption allows jailbreaking of iPhones for the sole purpose of allowing legally obtained applications to be added to the iPhone.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The exemption does not affect the contractual relations between Apple and an iPhone owner, for example, jailbreaking voiding the iPhone warranty; however, it is solely based on Apple's discretion on whether they will fix jailbroken devices in the event that they need to be repaired.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] At the same time, the Copyright Office exempted unlocking an iPhone from DMCA's anticircumvention prohibitions.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Unlocking an iPhone allows the iPhone to be used with any wireless carrier using the same GSM or CDMA technology for which the particular phone model was designed to operate.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Initially most wireless carriers in the US did not allow iPhone owners to unlock it for use with other carriers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] However AT&T allowed iPhone owners who had satisfied contract requirements to unlock their iPhone.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Instructions to unlock the device are available from Apple, but it is ultimately at the sole discretion of the carrier to authorize unlocking the device.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] This allows the use of a carrier-sourced iPhone on other networks.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Modern versions of iOS and the iPhone fully support LTE across multiple carriers wherever the phone was purchased.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Programs to remove SIM lock restrictions are available, but are not supported by Apple, and most often not a permanent unlock – a soft unlock, which modifies the iPhone so that the baseband will accept the SIM card of any GSM carrier.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] SIM unlocking is not jailbreaking, but a jailbreak is also required for these unofficial software unlocks.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] The legality of software unlocking varies in each country; for example, in the US, there is a DMCA exemption for unofficial software unlocking of devices purchased before January 26, 2013.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Competitor Microsoft, via a PR spokesman, criticized Apple's control over its platform.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Particularly at issue is the ability for Apple to remotely disable or delete apps at will.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Some in the tech community have expressed concern that the locked-down iOS represents a growing trend in Apple's approach to computing, particularly Apple's shift away from machines that hobbyists can "tinker with" and note the potential for such restrictions to stifle software innovation.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Former Facebook developer Joe Hewitt protested against Apple's control over its hardware as a "horrible precedent" but praised iOS's sandboxing of apps.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS utilizes many security features in both hardware and software.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] iOS is the second most popular mobile operating system in the world, after Android.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Sales of iPads in recent years are also behind Android, while, by web use (a proxy for all use), iPads (using iOS) are still the most popular.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] At WWDC 2014, Tim Cook said 800 million devices had been sold by June 2014.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] During Apple's quarterly earnings call in January 2015, the company announced that they had sold over one billion iOS devices since 2007.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] By February 2023, there were 2 billion devices activated, and 1.5 billion iPhones had been sold since 2007.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] By late 2011, iOS accounted for 60% of the market share for smartphones and tablets.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] By the end of 2014, iOS accounted for 14.8% of the smartphone market and 27.6% of the tablet and two-in-one market.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In May 2023, StatCounter reported iOS was used on 31.44% of smartphones and 55.75% of tablets worldwide, measured by internet usage instead of sales.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] In the third quarter of 2015, research from Strategy Analytics showed that iOS adoption of the worldwide smartphone market was at a record low 12.1%, attributed to lackluster performance in China and Africa.
[src:ios-app-hardening/ios] Android accounted for 87.5% of the market, with Windows Phone and BlackBerry accounting for the rest.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Keychains were initially developed for Apple's e-mail system, PowerTalk, in the early 1990s.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Among its many features, PowerTalk used plug-ins that allowed mail to be retrieved from a wide variety of mail servers and online services.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The keychain concept naturally "fell out" of this code, and was used in PowerTalk to manage all of a user's various login credentials for the various e-mail systems PowerTalk could connect to.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The passwords were not easily retrievable due to the encryption, yet the simplicity of the interface allowed the user to select a different password for every system without fear of forgetting them, as a single password would open the file and return them all.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] At the time, implementations of this concept were not available on other platforms.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Keychain was one of the few parts of PowerTalk that was obviously useful "on its own", which suggested it should be promoted to become a part of the basic Mac OS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] But due to internal politics, it was kept inside the PowerTalk system and, therefore, available to very few Mac users.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] It was not until the return of Steve Jobs in 1997 that Keychain concept was revived from the now-discontinued PowerTalk.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] By this point in time the concept was no longer so unusual, but it was still rare to see a keychain system that was not associated with a particular piece of application software, typically a web browser.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Keychain was later made a standard part of Mac OS 9, and was included in Mac OS X in the first commercial versions.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] In macOS, keychain files are stored in `~/Library/Keychains/` (and subdirectories), `/Library/Keychains/`, and `/Network/Library/Keychains/`, and the Keychain Access GUI application is located in the Utilities folder in the Applications folder.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] It is free, open source software released under the terms of the APSL-2.0.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The command line equivalent of Keychain Access is `/usr/bin/security`.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The keychain database is encrypted per-table and per-row with AES-256-GCM.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The time at which each credential is decrypted, how long it will remain decrypted, and whether the encrypted credential will be synced to iCloud varies depending on the type of data stored, and is documented on the Apple support website.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The default keychain file is the `login` keychain, typically unlocked on login by the user's login password, although the password for this keychain can instead be different from a user's login password, adding security at the expense of some convenience.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The Keychain Access application does not permit setting an empty password on a keychain.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The keychain may be set to be automatically "locked" if the computer has been idle for a time, and can be locked manually from the Keychain Access application.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] When locked, the password has to be re-entered next time the keychain is accessed, to unlock it.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Overwriting the file in `~/Library/Keychains/` with a new one (e.g. as part of a restore operation) also causes the keychain to lock and a password is required at next access.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] If the login keychain is protected by the login password, then the keychain's password will be changed whenever the login password is changed from within a logged-in session on macOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] On a shared Mac/non-Mac network, it is possible for the login keychain's password to lose synchronization if the user's login password is changed from a non-Mac system.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Also, if the password is changed from a directory service like Active Directory or Open Directory, or if the password is changed from another admin account e.g. using the System Preferences.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Some network administrators react to this by deleting the keychain file on logout, so that a new one will be created next time the user logs in.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] This means keychain passwords will not be remembered from one session to the next, even if the login password has not been changed.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] If this happens, the user can restore the keychain file in `~/Library/Keychains/` from a backup, but doing so will lock the keychain, which will then need to be unlocked at next use.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Keychain2Go could not be successfully updated by the developer to account for restrictions that Apple made to Keychain and access to Keychain in Mac OS X Sierra 10.12.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Keychain is distributed with both iOS and macOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] The iOS version is simpler because applications that run on mobile devices typically need only very basic Keychain features.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] For example, features such as ACLs (Access Control Lists) and sharing Keychain items between different apps are not present.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Thus, iOS Keychain items are only accessible to the app that created them.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] As Mac users’ default storage for sensitive information, Keychain is a prime target for security attacks.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] In 2019, 18-year-old German security researcher Linus Henze demonstrated his hack, dubbed KeySteal, that grabs passwords from the Keychain.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Initially, he withheld details of the hack, demanding Apple set up a bug bounty for macOS.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] Apple had however not done so when Henze subsequently revealed the hack.
[src:ios-app-hardening/keychain-software] It utilized Safari's access to security services, disguised as a utility in macOS that enables IT administrators to manipulate keychains.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Mobile application development presents certain security challenges that are unique compared to web applications and other forms of software.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet provides guidance on security considerations for mobile app development.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] It is not a comprehensive guide by any means, but rather a starting point for developers to consider security in their mobile app development.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For more information, see the Secure Product Design Cheat Sheet.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Developing with third-party libraries and components introduces the possibility of security unknowns.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] See the Vulnerable Dependency Management Cheat Sheet for recommendations on managing third-party dependencies when vulnerabilities are discovered.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Authentication is a complex topic and there are many pitfalls.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Authentication logic must be written and tested with extreme care.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] The tips here are only a starting point and barely scratch the surface.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For more information, see the Authentication Cheat Sheet and M1: Insecure Authentication/Authorization from the OWASP Mobile Top 10.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] See the Logging Cheat Sheet for examples of data that should not be logged.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is assigned to the Action Button (on iPhone 15 Pro and iPhone 16 Pro models), it can be executed by pressing the Action Button while the device is locked.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is assigned to the Control Center (on iOS/iPadOS 18+), it can be executed by pulling up the Control Center and pressing the Shortcut button while the device is locked.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] A Shortcut can be invoked via Siri while the device is locked.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is added to the user's Home Screen (on iOS/iPadOS 18+), it can be directly executed by tapping the Shortcut button on the user's lock screen while the device is locked.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is set to run at a specific interval or a specific time, it can execute even if the device is locked.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For further reading, visit the OWASP Mobile Top 10 Project.
[src:ios-app-hardening/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For a more detailed framework for mobile security, see the OWASP Mobile Application Security Project.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:ios-app-hardening/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:ios-app-hardening/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
